<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>Resident Thabo Madlala (31) said a large number of Ladysmith residents worked in Joburg and relied on taxis to transport them when they visited their loved ones on weekends.“The past few months have been very difficult. “We had to travel to neighbouring kasis to catch a taxi to Joburg. “It was very hard to adjust to that,” he said.Fikile Hlatshwayo (41), another resident, said it would be easier for her siblings in Joburg to visit home.In December, Daily Sun published a story about Kaunda’s decision to shut down the local and long distance taxis in Ladysmith.His decision followed the death of 11 people who were killed during a shooting associated with a taxi feud between the Klipriver and Sizwe taxi associations.However, in January Kaunda lifted the suspension on local taxi operators after residents staged a violent protest.The residents said the buses provided as a temporary measure were not enough.KZN Transport spokesman Mluleki Mntungwa said Kaunda visited the area yesterday to reopen the Joburg route.“It appears no harm will be caused by the reopening of a Joburg route. “There are other long distance routes that remain closed until further notice. “Intervention efforts are still underway.” Klipriver Taxi Association chairman Bhekuyise Masondo and Sizwe Taxi Association boss German Mabaso did not answer their cellphones or respond to the messages sent to them by the SunTeam.